  "prompt": "What happens to your phlegm after swallowing it?",
  "response": "When you swallow phlegm, it passes down your esophagus into your stomach. Once in the stomach, the phlegm is mixed with stomach acids and digestive enzymes. The components of phlegm, which primarily consist of water, mucins (glycoproteins), and various cells and particles, are broken down and digested in the stomach. \n\nThe body will absorb some of the water and nutrients, while other components are ultimately eliminated through the intestines as waste. Swallowing phlegm is generally a normal occurrence and usually not harmful, as the digestive system can handle it. However, if phlegm is excessive due to illness or infection, it's often advisable to consult a healthcare provider for appropriate treatment.",
